PROFESSOR 1: All right.

00:05:05.190 --> 00:05:07.020
Can you do it?

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:11.220
Yes, as in fact appears
on the slide here,

00:05:11.220 --> 00:05:13.920
there are a whole bunch of
little airports near us,

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:17.040
and we'll show them
on a subsequent slide.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:19.380
They all have flight
schools, and you

00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:23.310
can rent either airplanes
or helicopters or both,

00:05:23.310 --> 00:05:26.490
as well as find an
instructor to teach you.

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:30.570
You can actually learned
to fly in about 10 hours.

00:05:30.570 --> 00:05:32.310
To me, it's a little
bit unfortunate

00:05:32.310 --> 00:05:36.020
that so much emphasis is
placed on getting a pilot's

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:39.360
certificate, because it is
an independent achievement

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:43.020
to actually be able to take
off, cruise around, and land

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:47.220
without the instructor
having to touch anything.

00:05:47.220 --> 00:05:48.750
So that achievement,
unfortunately,

00:05:48.750 --> 00:05:51.000
isn't recognized with
a little certificate,

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:52.890
but that's actually
learning to fly.

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:58.170
The rest of the training,
which takes three times as long

00:05:58.170 --> 00:06:00.720
as actually learning
to fly, is directed

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:04.050
at flying a broken aircraft
or a lost aircraft,

00:06:04.050 --> 00:06:06.750
all this stuff that
prepares you to be

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:10.770
the only pilot in the aircraft,
which may not even be a goal.

00:06:10.770 --> 00:06:12.210
For passengers,
they would rather

00:06:12.210 --> 00:06:15.300
have two pilots in the
front not just one pilot,

00:06:15.300 --> 00:06:18.840
but there's a bizarre focus
on training one person

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:21.640
to do everything, which we'll
get into a little bit more.

