There were only 10 built. He
started as a little flight

00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:54.030
school at the local airport.

00:09:54.030 --> 00:09:57.270
He flies his little
Phemon 300 business

00:09:57.270 --> 00:09:58.840
jet all over the world.

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:03.220
So I think that's a
proof that flying is fun,

00:10:03.220 --> 00:10:04.830
because people who
could do anything

00:10:04.830 --> 00:10:06.990
that they want to do also fly.

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:08.490
You're going to
meet people from all

00:10:08.490 --> 00:10:11.010
around the world of
all different ages.

00:10:11.010 --> 00:10:15.060
It's a very diverse group,
especially if you like older

00:10:15.060 --> 00:10:19.760
guys, [LAUGHTER] which I do.

00:10:24.260 --> 00:10:25.260
Is it safe?

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:25.760
OK.

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:28.160
So we're going to show
you how to make it safe.

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:32.750
It's not safe statistically,
compared to JetBlue,

00:10:32.750 --> 00:10:36.020
but that's not because
little airplanes or feeble.

00:10:36.020 --> 00:10:39.260
As you'll see in this class, I
think it's because of the way

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:41.660
that people have
been flying them.

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:45.170
So we're going to show you how,
if you train like the airlines

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:49.460
and fly like the airlines, you
can get much closer to airline

00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:51.800
level of safety in
little airplanes,

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:54.860
as long as you're a little bit
conservative with the weather.

00:10:54.860 --> 00:10:58.610
And if all else fails, if
you're flying a modern design

00:10:58.610 --> 00:11:01.160
airplane, reach up and
pull the parachute.

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:03.200
And the whole airplane
will float down,

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:06.960
and you'll get out into a swamp.

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:07.460
All right.

00:11:07.460 --> 00:11:08.800
I'm taking mine back.

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:18.330
I thought that she was
on air, but she's not.

00:11:18.330 --> 00:11:18.910
OK.

00:11:18.910 --> 00:11:20.190
So this is me.

00:11:20.190 --> 00:11:21.900
I was class of 82 at MIT.

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:24.970
It was much more challenging
then than it is for you guys.

00:11:24.970 --> 00:11:27.840
That's because the Wisconsin ice
sheet was covering the campus

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:29.880
to a depth of about 100 feet.

00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:32.460
So we had to tunnel our
way from East Campus

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:34.410
into the main buildings.

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:36.570
I've been flying since 2002.

00:11:36.570 --> 00:11:42.270
I'm an instructor at East Coast
Aero Club at Hanscom Field.

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:44.460
I was also a regional jet pilot.

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:46.860
I decided to learn to fly
jets, and there's no better way

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:49.170
to do that than at the airlines.

00:11:49.170 --> 00:11:53.670
So I flew a 50-seat regional
jet called the CRJ, Canadair

00:11:53.670 --> 00:11:55.180
Regional Jet, for Delta.

00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:57.180
I have type ratings, which
we'll get into later.

00:11:57.180 --> 00:12:00.840
You need specific licensing for
each turbo jet powered aircraft

00:12:00.840 --> 00:12:02.220
that you fly.

00:12:02.220 --> 00:12:04.410
So I've got two of those.

00:12:04.410 --> 00:12:08.190
One of them is for the
smallest Cessna business jet.

00:12:08.190 --> 00:12:12.542
I usually fly though, these
days, a four-seat Cirrus,

00:12:12.542 --> 00:12:15.600
a Robinson R44, a
four-seat helicopter,

00:12:15.600 --> 00:12:22.260
and a Pilatus PC-12 which holds
either 11 people total or 60

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:25.440
sea turtles, which we'll
get into a little bit later.

